<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>In the loanable funds market, what happens when foreigners increase their investment in domestic markets?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Supply shifts right, interest rates fall, quantity increases</option>
            <option letter="b">Supply shifts left, interest rates rise, quantity decreases</option>
            <option letter="c">Demand shifts right, interest rates rise, quantity increases</option>
            <option letter="d">Demand shifts left, interest rates fall, quantity decreases</option>
        </options>
        <answer>a</answer>
        <explanation>When foreigners invest more in domestic markets, they increase the supply of loanable funds available at each interest rate (shifting the supply curve right). This greater supply leads to lower equilibrium interest rates and a larger quantity of funds being loaned in the market.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
